This is an interesting materials-design challenge because the requirements pull in opposite directions:

* It has to insulate from hot sand.
* It can’t be greasy (or sand will stick).
* It has to survive saltwater.
* It has to be biodegradable.
* It has to be non-toxic for people and marine life.
* It should disappear naturally after use.

I’d approach it like a “temporary second skin” rather than a sunscreen.

Project: SandShield

Imagine a clear spray that dries in 20–30 seconds into a paper-thin, flexible foam-like coating.

Layer 1 — Bioadhesive Base

A breathable film that bonds lightly to skin.

Possible ingredients:

* Sodium alginate (from seaweed)
* Pullulan (fermented starch)
* Cellulose nanofibers
* Glycerol for flexibility

This creates the temporary skin.

⸻

Layer 2 — Thermal Barrier

This is the magic.

Suspend microscopic hollow particles inside the film:

* Hollow cellulose microspheres
* Hollow silica microcapsules
* Lignin aerogel particles
* Chitosan aerogel beads

These trap air.

Air is the actual insulator.

Instead of your skin touching 150°F sand directly, heat must move through millions of tiny air pockets.

⸻

Layer 3 — Low-Stick Surface

The outer layer should have extremely low surface energy.

Instead of silicone or PFAS, use biodegradable alternatives:

* Carnauba wax nanoparticles
* Rice bran wax
* Candelilla wax
* Cellulose stearate

These dry almost matte.

Sand falls off instead of embedding.

⸻

Cooling Additive

Instead of menthol (which tricks nerves), use evaporative cooling during application:

* Purified water
* Ethanol (rapid evaporation)
* Aloe extract

Initial cooling:
5–10°F perceived reduction.

⸻

Mineral Reflector

Tiny amounts of:

* Micronized titanium dioxide
* Zinc oxide

These reflect infrared radiation from the hot sand.

Since they’re embedded in the film, they don’t create a chalky sunscreen look.

